  <section id="dateieinaus">
  <paragraph id="hd_id3156344" role="heading" level="1" oldref="1" l10n="U" xml-lang="en-US"><link href="text/sbasic/shared/03020000.xhp" name="File I/O Functions">File I/O Functions</link></paragraph>
  <paragraph role="paragraph" id="par_id3153360" l10n="U" xml-lang="en-US" oldref="2">Use File I/O functions to create and manage user-defined (data) files.</paragraph>
  </section>
  <paragraph role="paragraph" id="par_id3150398" l10n="U" xml-lang="en-US" oldref="3">You can use these functions to support the creation of &quot;relative&quot; files, so that you can save and reload certain records by specifying their record number. File I/O functions can also help you manage your files by providing you with information such as file size, current path settings, or the creation date of a file or a directory.</paragraph>
